'''Louis "Studs" Terkel''' (May 16, 1912&nbsp;– October 31, 2008)<ref>{{cite news | author=Rick Kogan | title=Studs Terkel dies | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-studs-terkel-dead,0,2321576.story | work=The Chicago Tribune | date=31 October 2008 | accessdate=2008-11-13}}</ref> was an American author, historian, actor, and broadcaster. He received the [[Pulitzer Prize for General Non-Fiction]] in 1985 for ''[[The Good War]]'', and is best remembered for his [[oral history|oral histories]] of common Americans, and for hosting a long-running radio show in Chicago.

==Early life==
Terkel was born to [[History of the Jews in Russia|Russian Jewish]] immigrants, Samuel Terkel, a tailor, and Anna (Annie) Finkel, a seamstress, in New York City.<ref>{{cite news | author=William Grimes | title=Studs Terkel, Listener to Americans, Dies at 96 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/01/books/01terkel.html?_r=1 | work=The New York Times | date=31 October 2008 | accessdate=2008-11-17}}</ref> At the age of eight he moved with his family to [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]], [[Illinois]], where he spent most of his life. He had two brothers, Ben (1907–1965) and Meyer (1905–1958). He attended [[McKinley High School (Chicago)|McKinley High School]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Studs Terkel |title=Studs Terkel's Chicago |location=New York |publisher=New Press |year=2012 |isbn=9781595587183 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yYs4AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q&f=false |pages=46–47 }}</ref>

From 1926 to 1936, his parents ran a [[rooming house]] that also served as a meeting place for people from all walks of life. Terkel credited his understanding of humanity and social interaction to the tenants and visitors who gathered in the lobby there, and the people who congregated in nearby [[Bughouse Square]]. In 1939, he married Ida Goldberg (1912–1999), and the couple had one son. Although he received his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from the [[University of Chicago Law School]] in 1934 (and was admitted to the Illinois Bar the following year), he decided instead of practicing law, he wanted to be a [[concierge]] at a hotel, and he soon joined a theater group.<ref>{{cite news | author=Jane Ammeson | title=Storytelling with Studs Terkel | work=[[Chicago Life]] | url=http://chicagolife.net/content/interview/Storytelling_with_Studs_Terkel | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808212436/http://chicagolife.net/content/interview/Storytelling_with_Studs_Terkel | dead-url=yes | archive-date=2007-08-08 }}</ref>

==Career==
A political [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]], Terkel joined the [[Works Progress Administration]]'s [[Federal Writers' Project]], working in [[radio broadcasting|radio]], doing work that varied from voicing [[soap opera]] productions and announcing [[Broadcast journalism|news]] and [[sportscaster|sport]]s, to presenting shows of recorded [[music]] and writing radio scripts and advertisements. His well-known radio program, titled ''The Studs Terkel Program'', aired on 98.7 [[WFMT]] Chicago between 1952 and 1997.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Richard Sisson|author2=Christian K. Zacher |author3=Andrew Robert Lee Cayton |title=The American Midwest: an interpretive encyclopedia|publisher=Indiana University Press|year=2007|pages=498}}<br>Previous Terkel radio work included WENR (1944 ''Wax Museum''), WCFL (beginning November 30, 1947). A TV show (''Stud's Place'', beginning November, 1949) lasted to 1951.</ref> The one-hour program was broadcast each weekday during those forty-five years. On this program, he interviewed guests as diverse as [[Martin Luther King]], [[Leonard Bernstein]], [[Mort Sahl]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Alexander Frey]], [[Dorothy Parker]], [[Tennessee Williams]], [[Jean Shepherd]], and [[Big Bill Broonzy]].

In the late 1940s and early 1950s, Terkel was also the central character of ''Studs' Place'', an unscripted television drama about the owner of a [[greasy spoon|greasy-spoon]] diner in Chicago through which many famous people and interesting characters passed. This show, along with [[Marlin Perkins]]'s ''[[Zoo Parade]]'', ''[[Garroway at Large]]'' and the children's show ''[[Kukla, Fran, and Ollie]]'', are widely considered canonical examples of the [[Chicago School of Television]].

Terkel published his first book, ''[[Giants of Jazz (Terkel book)|Giants of Jazz]]'', in 1956. He followed it in 1967 with his first collection of [[oral history|oral histories]], ''Division Street America'' with 70 people talking about effect on the human spirit of living in an American metropolis.<ref name="newpress">{{cite web|title=Division Street America by Studs Terkel|url=http://thenewpress.com/books/division-street|accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name="aintlyon">{{cite news|author=Peter Lyon |title=Chicago Voices|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/09/26/specials/terkel-division.html|accessdate=September 27, 2016|work=Books|publisher=[[New York Times]]|date=February 5, 1967}}</ref><ref name="chmrecordings">{{cite web|title=Studs Terkel, Recordings from Division Street|url=http://studsterkel.matrix.msu.edu/dstreet.php|website=Chicago History Museum|accessdate=September 27, 2016}} 23 original audio recordings as aired by Terkel</ref>

He also served as a distinguished scholar-in-residence at the [[Chicago History Museum]]. He appeared in the film ''[[Eight Men Out]]'', based on the [[Black Sox Scandal]], in which he played newspaper reporter [[Hugh Fullerton]], who tries to uncover the White Sox players' plans to throw the [[1919 World Series]]. Terkel found it particularly amusing to play this role, as he was a big fan of the [[Chicago White Sox]] (as well as a vocal critic of major league baseball during the 1994 baseball strike), and gave a moving congratulatory speech to the White Sox organization after their [[2005 World Series]] championship during a television interview.

Terkel received his [[nickname]] while he was acting in a play with another person named Louis. To keep the two straight, the director of the production gave Terkel the nickname ''Studs'' after the fictional character about whom Terkel was reading at the time—[[Studs Lonigan]], of [[James T. Farrell]]'s trilogy.

Terkel was acclaimed for his efforts to preserve [[oral history|American oral history]]. His 1985 book ''[[The Good War|"The Good War": An Oral History of World War Two]]'', which detailed ordinary peoples' accounts of the country's involvement in World War II, won the [[Pulitzer Prize]]. For ''[[Hard Times: An Oral History of the Great Depression]]'', Terkel assembled recollections of the [[Great Depression]] that spanned the socioeconomic spectrum, from [[Okie]]s, through prison inmates, to the wealthy. His 1974 book, ''[[Working (book)|Working]]'', in which (as reflected by its subtitle) ''People Talk About What They Do All Day and How They Feel About What They Do'', also was highly acclaimed. ''Working'' was made into a short-lived [[Working (musical)|Broadway show of the same title]] in 1978 and was telecast on [[PBS]] in 1982. In 1995, he received the [[Chicago History Museum]] "Making History Award" for Distinction in Journalism and Communications. In 1997, Terkel was elected a member of [[The American Academy of Arts and Letters]]. Two years later, he received the [[George Polk Awards|George Polk Career Award]] in 1999.

==Later life==
[[File:Studs Terkel.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Studs Terkel before his 95th birthday party at the Chicago History Museum]]

In 2004, Terkel received the [[Elijah P. Lovejoy|Elijah Parish Lovejoy]] Award as well as an honorary [[Doctor of Laws]] degree from [[Colby College]]. In August 2005, Terkel underwent successful [[open-heart surgery]]. At the age of ninety-three, he was one of the oldest people to undergo this form of surgery and doctors reported his recovery to be remarkable for someone of that advanced age. Terkel smoked two cigars a day until 2004.

On May 22, 2006, Terkel, along with other plaintiffs, including [[Quentin Young]], filed a suit in federal district court against [[AT&T Inc.]], to stop the telecommunications carrier from giving customer telephone records to the [[National Security Agency]] without a court order.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/safefree/nsaspying/25625prs20060522.html|title=Author Studs Terkel, Other Prominent Chicagoans Join in Challenge to AT&T Sharing of Telephone Records with the National Security Agency|author=|date=|website=aclu.org|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref>

{{quote|Having been blacklisted from working in television during the [[Joe McCarthy|McCarthy]] era, I know the harm of government using private corporations to intrude into the lives of innocent Americans. When government uses the telephone companies to create massive databases of all our phone calls it has gone too far.}}

The lawsuit was dismissed by Judge [[Matthew F. Kennelly]] on July 26, 2006. Judge Kennelly cited a "[[state secrets privilege]]" designed to protect national security from being harmed by lawsuits.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsmax.com/archives/ic/2006/7/25/173512.shtml |title=Judge Drops Studs Terkel NSA Lawsuit |publisher=NewsMax.com |date=July 25, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120132800/http://archive.newsmax.com/archives/ic/2006/7/25/173512.shtml |archivedate=January 20, 2008 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>

In an interview in ''[[The Guardian]]'' celebrating his 95th birthday, Terkel discussed his own "diverse and idiosyncratic taste in music, from [[Bob Dylan]] to [[Alexander Frey]], [[Louis Armstrong]] to [[Woody Guthrie]]".<ref name="guardian">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2008/jan/23/history.usa |title=Let Me Tell You A Story |author=Gary Younge |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 23, 2008 }}</ref>

Terkel published a new personal memoir entitled ''Touch and Go'' in fall 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/reviews/2007-12-19-terkel_N.htm|title=Terkel records life in a 'Touch and Go' way |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=December 19, 2007 |accessdate=October 15, 2017}}</ref>

Terkel was a self-described [[Agnosticism|agnostic]],<ref>{{cite book | year=2006 | title=This I Believe: The Personal Philosophies of Remarkable Men and Women | editor1=Jay Allison |editor2=Dan Gediman }}</ref> which he jokingly defined as "a cowardly atheist" during a 2004 interview with [[Krista Tippett]] on [[American Public Media]]'s ''[[Speaking of Faith]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onbeing.org/program/studs-terkel-life-faith-and-death/180|title=Studs Terkel — Life, Faith, and Death -|author=|date=|website=onbeing.org|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref>

One of his last interviews was for the documentary ''Soul of a People'' on [[Smithsonian Channel]]. He spoke about his participation in the [[Works Progress Administration]].

At his last public appearance, in 2007, Terkel said he was "still in touch—but ready to go".<ref name="chicagotribuneobit">{{cite news | author=Rick Kogan | title=Studs Terkel dies | newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=2008-10-31 | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-studs-terkel-dead,0,2321576.story}}</ref> He gave one of his last interviews on the [[BBC]] ''[[Hardtalk]]'' program on February 4, 2008.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/hardtalk/7226682.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Studs Terkel | date=February 4, 2008 | accessdate=April 1, 2010}}</ref> He spoke of the imminent election of [[Barack Obama]] as President of the United States, and offered him some advice, in October 2008.<ref name=HuffingtonPost>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/edward-lifson/studs-for-obama_b_137278.html|author=[[Edward Lifson]]|title=Studs for Obama|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=November 23, 2008}}</ref>

Terkel died in his Chicago home on Friday, October 31, 2008 at the age of ninety-six. He had been suffering ever since a fall in his home earlier that month.<ref>{{wikinews-inline|American prize-winning author Studs Terkel dead at 96}}</ref>

==Legacy and audio recordings==
{{main|Studs Terkel Radio Archive}}
{{external media | width = 210px | float = right | audio1 = [https://soundcloud.com/studsterkel-radio-archive/louis-daniel-armstrong-talks-with-studs-terkel-on-wfmt-1962624 Louis Daniel Armstrong talks with Studs Terkel on WFMT ; 1962/6/24], 33:43, [[Studs Terkel Radio Archive]]<ref name="studs1">{{cite web | title =Louis Daniel Armstrong talks with Studs Terkel on WFMT ; 1962/6/24 | work = | publisher =[[Studs Terkel Radio Archive]] | date = June 24, 1962 | url =https://soundcloud.com/studsterkel-radio-archive/tracks | accessdate =September 27, 2016 }}</ref> 
| audio2 = [https://soundcloud.com/studsterkel-radio-archive/gwendolyn-brooks-talks-with-studs-pt-1-poetry-month-1967 Poet Laureate Gwendolyn Brooks talks with Studs – Poetry Month ; 1967], 45:01, [[Studs Terkel Radio Archive]]<ref name="studs2">{{cite web | title =Poet Laureate Gwendolyn Brooks talks with Studs – Poetry Month ; 1967 | work = | publisher =[[Studs Terkel Radio Archive]] | date = 1967 | url = https://soundcloud.com/studsterkel-radio-archive/gwendolyn-brooks-talks-with-studs-pt-1-poetry-month-1967 | accessdate =September 27, 2016}}</ref>
| audio3 = [http://blogs.loc.gov/now-see-hear/2014/07/studs-terkels-music-interviews/  Studs Terkel's Music Interviews], includes excerpts of interviews with [[Bob Dylan]], [[Janis Joplin]], [[Oscar Petersen]], and [[Memphis Slim]]. [[Library of Congress]]<ref name="studsLOC">{{cite web | title =Studs Terkel's Music Interviews | work = | publisher =[[Library of Congress]] | date = 2014 | url = http://blogs.loc.gov/now-see-hear/2014/07/studs-terkels-music-interviews/ | accessdate =September 27, 2016 }} Includes excerpts of interviews with [[Bob Dylan]], [[Janis Joplin]], [[Oscar Petersen]], and [[Memphis Slim]].</ref>}}
In 1998, Terkel and WFMT, the radio station which broadcast Terkel's long-running program, had donated approximately 7,000 tape recordings of Terkel's interviews and broadcasts to the [[Chicago History Museum]]. In 2010, the Museum and the Library of Congress announced a multi-year joint collaboration to digitally preserve and make available at both institutions these recordings, which the Library of Congress called, "a remarkably rich history of the ideas and perspectives of both common and influential people living in the second half of the 20th century." "For Studs, there was not a voice that should not be heard, a story that could not be told," said Gary T. Johnson, Museum president. "He believed that everyone had the right to be heard and had something important to say. He was there to listen, to chronicle, and to make sure their stories are remembered."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2010/10-115.html|title=Library Collaborates With Chicago History Museum                         To Preserve Radio Icon Studs Terkel's Historic Recordings|author=|date=|website=loc.gov|accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref> In 2014 WFMT and the [[Chicago History Museum]] announced the creation of the website, Studsterkel.org (see studsterkel.wfmt.com), which will house the entire archive of Studs Terkel interviews.

==Awards and honors==
In 1982, Terkel was awarded an honorary Doctor of Humane Letters from the [[University of Illinois at Chicago]].<ref>
http://www.uic.edu/depts/ovcsa/commencement/commencement_history.shtml</ref>

In 1985, Terkel received the [[Pulitzer Prize for General Non-Fiction]] for his book ''[[The Good War]]''.

In 2001, Terkel was inducted into the [[Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame]] as a Friend of the Community.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glhalloffame.org/index.pl?page=inductees&todo=year |title=Inductees to the Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame |publisher=Chicago Gay and Lesbian Hall of Fame |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006224109/http://www.glhalloffame.org/index.pl?page=inductees&todo=year |archivedate=October 6, 2010 }}</ref>

In 2004, Terkel was inducted as a Laureate of [[The Lincoln Academy of Illinois]] and awarded the ''Order of Lincoln'' (the State's highest honor) by the Governor of Illinois in the area of Communications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thelincolnacademyofillinois.org/4632-2/#toggle-id-12|title=Laureates by Year |publisher=The Lincoln Academy of Illinois |access-date=2016-03-07}}</ref>

In 2006, Terkel received the Lifetime Achievement Award from the Dayton Literary Peace Prize, the first and only annual U.S. literary award recognizing the power of the written word to promote peace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daytonliterarypeaceprize.org/winners.htm|title=Dayton Literary Peace Prize – Award Winners|publisher=Dayton Literary Peace Prize Foundation|date= |accessdate=15 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2006-07-19-terkel_x.htm |title=Studs Terkel to receive first Dayton literary prize |newspaper=USA Today |date=July 19, 2006 |agency=AP }}</ref>

In 2010, Terkel was inducted into the Chicago Literary Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://chicagoliteraryhof.org/inductees/profile/studs-terkel |title=Studs Terkel |date=2010 |website=Chicago Literary Hall of Fame |language=en |access-date=2017-10-15}}</ref>

